org/web/20141129233846/http://www-01.ibm.com/software/globalization/ccsid/ccsid949.html IBM Code Page 949]\n*[http://demo.icu-project.org/icu-bin/convexp?conv=ibm-949_P110-1999&s=ALL ICU Demonstration mapping IBM-949 to Unicode]\n*[http://demo.icu-project.org/icu-bin/convexp?conv=ibm-949_P11A-1999&s=ALL ICU Demonstration mapping IBM-949C (ASCII based variant) to Unicode]\n\n{{character encoding}}\n\n[[Category:Character sets|949]]\n[[Category:Encodings of Asian languages]]\n\n{{compu-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{context|date=May 2018}}\n{{no footnotes|date=January 2019}}\n[[File:IBM Korea KS PC-Data encoding (IBM-949).svg|thumb|Layout of the IBM-949 code page]]\n'''IBM code page 949''' (IBM-949) is IBM's PC Data KS code. It implements [[EUC-KR]] in addition to encodings for IBM extensions including [[Private Use Areas#Private-use characters in other character sets|user defined characters]]. This [[code page]] supports the [[Korean language]]. It is a combination of the single-byte '''Code page 1088''' and the double-byte [[Code page 951]].\n\nBytes 0x00 through 0x7F are used for single byte KS X 1003 ([[ISO 646]]:KR) characters, a similar set to ASCII. Bytes 0x80 through 0x84 are used for IBM single byte extension characters. Lead bytes 0x8F through 0xA0 are used for IBM double byte extension characters. Lead bytes 0xA1 through 0xFE are used for Wansung code ([[KS X 1001]] characters in EUC-KR form, double byte).\n\nIBM-949 should not be confused with [[Unified Hangul Code|Windows code page 949]] (IBM-1363), which is Microsoft's Unified Hangul Code, a different extension of EUC-KR, nor with plain EUC-KR ([[Code page 970|IBM-970]]).\n\n== Single byte codes ==\n\n{|{{chset-tableformat}}\n{{chset-table-header|Code page 949}}\n|-\n!{{chset-left2|0_<br/>0}}\n|{{chset-color-ctrl}}|{{chset-ctrl|0000|[[Null character|NUL]]|0}}\n|{{chset-color-graph-box}}|{{chset-cell|250C|[[\u250c]]|1}}\n|{{chset-color-graph-box}}|{{chset-cell|2510|[[\u2510]]|2}}\n|{{chset-color-graph-box}}|{{